Fiat was wrong to turn off the Volt. Volt is the same concept as the BMW i3 Rexx, an extended-range electric vehicle (EREV). Normally, the Volt has a range of 44 miles (55-60 in new models) with an electric generator powered by a gasoline engine that is active when the battery is deemed to be exhausted. A driver can accelerate one Volt fully to top speed and the gasoline generator does not turn on until the battery is empty. A plug-in hybrid would require the help of a gasoline engine to accelerate in these conditions and many less demanding conditions.

For those who use these stations, please help us, the community of ChaDeMo. Only charge for as long as you need to go home, and connect your vehicle to your home, do not abuse the chargers, others need them as well. Please leave a note on your vehicle or on PlugShare if and when it would be acceptable to disconnect your vehicle if you are not nearby and / or need contact information to check. If your car is equipped with a disconnect alarm and you cannot be connected to your home, please disable the alarm. Specifically, to the Tesla I noticed that you are parked and connected for hours every day. Unless you have a VERY long drive to campus, I would assume that you are abusing the system by not connecting to your home. In any case, please help the community in one of a few ways. If the person who has done this is reading this, and so are others. If a car is being charged, please do not take your car off. Many people who have electric cars may not have places to charge at home because they live in apartment buildings, they may not even have an off-street parking space. And even if they do have off-street parking, they may not be allowed or have control over installing a charger in an apartment parking lot. Plus, there are many other places nearby if you need emergency power. And, if you are in a hybrid vehicle with power, it is completely wrong to unplug an all-electric car that does not have the facilities you need to just walk to a gas station and refuel in less than a minute at thousands of locations in the city. Please be considerate with others in the community. If you have problems with this, please share your views for a discussion with the rest of us to explore this important issue.

I think a lot of Leaf drivers don't realize that fast charging over 80% is not fast charging. Below about 60% you charge at about 120 Amps, it tapers off. The charger drops the delivered Amps very steeply. They probably charge just as fast at Level 2 over about 90%. I waited while a guy charges at well over 95%. It charges at a paltry 9 Amps. I showed the guy and said, "You charge at 9 Amps, it takes 15 minutes to complete the last few percent," he seemed angry and said, "You throw me out? Just take the charger." I feel like a jerk, but he's wasting our time. I just thought I'd give a PSA.

Fiat was wrong to turn off the Volt. Volt is the same concept as the BMW i3 Rexx, an extended-range electric vehicle (EREV). Normally, the Volt has a range of 44 miles (55-60 in new models) with an electric generator powered by a gasoline engine that is active when the battery is deemed to be exhausted. A driver can accelerate one Volt fully to top speed and the gasoline generator does not turn on until the battery is empty. A plug-in hybrid would require the help of a gasoline engine to accelerate in these conditions and many less demanding conditions.

"Cost" refers to a Level 3 charger. There is no Level 3 charger. There are Level 3 chargers in Europe, but this station is not located in Europe. The normal 240V charger is based on the AC Level 2 standard SAE J1772. There is an AC Level 3 standard SAE J1772, but it is a 240V 3-phase standard that has not been adopted by any automaker in the U.S. The CCS chargers common at many charging stations are based on the DC Level 2 standard SAE J1772. CHAdeMO chargers are not based on the SAE J1772 standard and therefore the level designations do not apply.

Joel, If you haven't been watching the prices of the EV fast charger, I can understand your reaction to our price. Here's an example of our fast charger competition. The Blink network charges $0.65 / kWh ($0.59 for members) and eVgo charges $4.95 + $0.20 / minute or & gt; $10 for a 30-minute charge. Average fast charging at our site is about 10 kWh, which would be $8.90 for a charge of about 30 minutes. Both Blink and eVgo networks have been built on government subsidies with equipment not intended for a coastal environment. In terms of consumption, we haven't seen a dramatic increase in consumption when technical problems prompted us to offer fast charging for free this summer, and we haven't seen a dramatic drop in consumption now that we've resumed charging for electricity. We're constrained by our costs. Commercial electricity costs $0.24 / kWh, and we risk a $3.00 charge when the fast charger causes us to peak demand.
